<% title_actions link_to(_("New System Group"), new_systemgroup_path) %>
<% title _("System group configuration") %>
<div id="welcome">
  <p>
  <%= _('A system group is in some ways similar to an inherited node declaration, in that it is a high level grouping of classes that can be named and treated as a unit. This is then treated as a template and  is selectable during the creation of a new system and ensures that the system is configured in one of your pre-defined states.') %>

  <%= _('In addition to defining which puppet classes get included when building this system type you are also able to assign variables and provisioning information to a system group to further refine the behavior of the puppet runtime.') %>

  <%= _("The system group's classes and the system group's variables are included in the external node information when the puppetmaster compiles the system's configuration.") %>
  </p>

  <p>
  <%= _('There are two strategies when using system groups.') %>

  <%= _('You may create puppet classes that represent high-level system configurations, for example, a <b>system-type-ldap-server</b> class, which includes all the required functionality from other modules or you may decide to create a system group called <b>system-type-ldap-server</b> and add the required classes into the system group configuration.').html_safe %>

  <%= _('These two options are personal decisions and are up to you (where the main difference would be the parameter/variables settings).') %>
  </p>

</div>
